# Splunk credential file
# Copy this file to ./credentials (in the project root) and fill in your values:
#
#   cp credentials.example credentials
#   chmod 600 credentials
#   # Edit credentials with your actual values
#
# This file is read automatically by all skill scripts.
# The real credentials file is gitignored and will NOT be committed.
# Values are literal strings; shell expressions are not executed.
# The helper supports simple ${OTHER_KEY} references from this file.
# To use a different credentials file entirely, set:
#   export SPLUNK_CREDENTIALS_FILE="/path/to/credentials.cloud"

# --- Optional platform override ---
# In normal use, leave SPLUNK_PLATFORM unset and the scripts will infer the
# target from the current operation plus your Cloud/REST settings.
# If one credentials file contains both a Cloud stack and an Enterprise/HF REST
# target, interactive scripts will prompt when a run is ambiguous.
# If this file contains both Cloud ACS settings and a search-tier REST target,
# set SPLUNK_PLATFORM="cloud" for cloud-only runs so non-interactive automation
# does not stop to ask which platform you intended.
# For non-interactive hybrid runs, set one of these explicitly:
# SPLUNK_PLATFORM="enterprise"
# SPLUNK_PLATFORM="cloud"

# --- Optional runtime role declaration ---
# Use these values when you want warning-only placement checks to know what tier
# the current management endpoint represents.
# - SPLUNK_TARGET_ROLE describes the primary/profile target for the run.
# - SPLUNK_SEARCH_TARGET_ROLE describes the paired runtime role when this run
#   has a second target or companion runtime.
# - Environment values override the selected profile's role metadata for the
#   current run.
# - If SPLUNK_PLATFORM=cloud, warning-only checks stay anchored to the Cloud
#   search tier even when a paired HF or UF profile is present.
# - For forwarder-side REST actions in hybrid mode, either select the forwarder
#   profile directly or set SPLUNK_PLATFORM="enterprise" for that run.
# SPLUNK_TARGET_ROLE="search-tier"
# SPLUNK_SEARCH_TARGET_ROLE="heavy-forwarder"

# --- Optional topology-aware profile selectors ---
# Use these when one run spans different management planes:
# - SPLUNK_INGEST_PROFILE points index and HEC management at the ingest tier.
# - SPLUNK_DEPLOYER_PROFILE stages clustered search-tier app/config bundle changes.
# - SPLUNK_CLUSTER_MANAGER_PROFILE stages clustered indexer bundle changes.
# - SPLUNK_HEC_URL provides the runtime collector URL for SC4x or other HEC-based
#   integrations when it should not be inferred from a REST management host.
# - SPLUNK_DELIVERY_PLANE=auto is the default. Use bundle to force clustered
#   bundle delivery or rest to force single-endpoint REST behavior.
# SPLUNK_INGEST_PROFILE="hf"
# SPLUNK_DEPLOYER_PROFILE="deployer"
# SPLUNK_CLUSTER_MANAGER_PROFILE="cluster_manager"
# SPLUNK_HEC_URL="https://hf.example.com:8088/services/collector/event"
# SPLUNK_DELIVERY_PLANE="auto"

# --- Search-tier REST API access ---
# These values are used for app-specific REST configuration and validation.
# For Splunk Cloud, access to :8089 requires the search-api allow list to include
# your source IP, and sc_admin cannot use these endpoints for app install,
# index creation, or restart operations. Those tasks use ACS instead.
# For Splunk Cloud, SPLUNK_URI is usually the full search-tier host on :8089,
# such as https://example-searchhead.splunkcloud.com:8089 for production or
# https://example-searchhead.stg.splunkcloud.com:8089 for staging. The ACS
# fields below use only the URL prefixes, not the full hostnames.
SPLUNK_HOST="your-splunk-host"
SPLUNK_MGMT_PORT="8089"
SPLUNK_SEARCH_API_URI="https://your-splunk-host:8089"
# Legacy alias kept for backward compatibility
SPLUNK_URI="${SPLUNK_SEARCH_API_URI}"
SPLUNK_USER=""
SPLUNK_PASS=""

# --- SSL verification ---
# By default, Splunk REST calls keep compatibility mode and skip TLS
# certificate verification (-k) because on-prem Splunk commonly uses
# self-signed certs. Set SPLUNK_VERIFY_SSL="true" to use system trust, or set
# SPLUNK_CA_CERT to verify against a specific CA bundle or PEM file.
# SPLUNK_VERIFY_SSL="false"
# SPLUNK_CA_CERT="/path/to/splunk-ca.pem"

# --- Enterprise-only remote package staging ---
# Used for Enterprise app installs when the Splunk host cannot read the local
# workstation package path directly.
SPLUNK_SSH_HOST="your-splunk-host"
SPLUNK_SSH_PORT="22"
SPLUNK_SSH_USER="splunk"
SPLUNK_SSH_PASS=""
# Optional remote host-bootstrap behavior for Linux install/configure workflows.
# SPLUNK_REMOTE_TMPDIR="/tmp"
# SPLUNK_REMOTE_SUDO="true"   # assume root SSH or non-interactive sudo on target

# --- Splunk Cloud ACS settings ---
# Required for Splunk Cloud app installs, index management, and restarts.
# IMPORTANT: ACS values are not always the same as the friendly
# *.splunkcloud.com search-tier hostnames.
# - SPLUNK_CLOUD_STACK must be the ACS stack identifier that ACS accepts in:
#     acs config add-stack "<stack>"
#   If acs login returns 404-stack-not-found, the stack value is still wrong.
# - SPLUNK_CLOUD_SEARCH_HEAD is OPTIONAL and must be the ACS target search-head
#   prefix, typically something like:
#     sh-i-0910d0dfdb9ed913a
#     shc1
#   It is NOT the friendly hostname like
#     example-searchhead.stg.splunkcloud.com
# The correct ACS stack/search-head values come from Splunk Cloud provisioning
# details or the instructions provided with the deployment.
# Safe workflow:
#   1) Set SPLUNK_CLOUD_SEARCH_HEAD="" unless you know the ACS target prefix.
#   2) Verify the stack with:
#        acs config add-stack "<stack>"
#        acs config use-stack "<stack>"
#        acs login --token-user "<stack_token_user>"
#   3) Only add --target-sh after you have the exact ACS search-head prefix.
SPLUNK_CLOUD_STACK=""
SPLUNK_CLOUD_SEARCH_HEAD=""
SPLUNK_CLOUD_INDEX_SEARCHABLE_DAYS="90"
ACS_SERVER="https://admin.splunk.com"
# For *.stg.splunkcloud.com stacks, use:
# ACS_SERVER="https://staging.admin.splunk.com"

# ACS authentication:
# Option 1: provide a cached stack token (recommended for SAML users).
#   Use this if you normally sign in with SSO/SAML or do not have a stack-local
#   username/password that ACS can use.
STACK_TOKEN=""
# Option 2: provide stack-local credentials plus the token user to let ACS CLI
# create and cache a token automatically.
#   STACK_TOKEN_USER is the value passed to:
#     acs login --token-user "<value>"
#   If you use stack-local credentials, this is usually the same value as
#   STACK_USERNAME.
#   Without STACK_TOKEN, ACS automation requires all three of:
#     STACK_USERNAME, STACK_PASSWORD, and STACK_TOKEN_USER
STACK_USERNAME=""
STACK_PASSWORD=""
STACK_TOKEN_USER=""

# --- Splunkbase / splunk.com credentials ---
# Used for direct Splunkbase downloads and ACS app install/update commands.
# If SPLUNK_USERNAME / SPLUNK_PASSWORD below are blank, ACS reuses SB_USER / SB_PASS.
SB_USER=""
SB_PASS=""

# Optional explicit Splunk.com credentials for ACS app operations.
SPLUNK_USERNAME="${SB_USER}"
SPLUNK_PASSWORD="${SB_PASS}"

# External HTTPS policy:
# - Splunkbase uses certificate verification by default. Override only when
#   you intentionally need compatibility mode or a custom corporate CA.
# - Remote app downloads inherit the Splunk TLS behavior by default so
#   existing self-signed workflows continue to work. Override them separately
#   if the download endpoint needs different trust settings.
# SPLUNKBASE_VERIFY_SSL="true"
# SPLUNKBASE_CA_CERT="/path/to/splunkbase-ca.pem"
# APP_DOWNLOAD_VERIFY_SSL="${SPLUNK_VERIFY_SSL}"
# APP_DOWNLOAD_CA_CERT="${SPLUNK_CA_CERT}"

# --- Multi-target profile support ---
# Use profiles when one file needs multiple targets such as Cloud, HF, and
# on-prem. Keep the flat keys above for a single default target, or define
# PROFILE_<name>__KEY entries and select them with SPLUNK_PROFILE.
#
# Hybrid example:
# - Keep SPLUNK_PROFILE on the platform / ACS target.
# - Set SPLUNK_SEARCH_PROFILE to override only search-tier REST and SSH settings.
# - Set SPLUNK_INGEST_PROFILE for Enterprise HEC/index actions when ingest lives
#   on a different tier such as HF or an indexer cluster manager.
# - Set SPLUNK_DEPLOYER_PROFILE and/or SPLUNK_CLUSTER_MANAGER_PROFILE for
#   clustered Enterprise bundle delivery.
# - Keep SPLUNK_TARGET_ROLE on the primary Cloud/search-tier target.
# - Use SPLUNK_SEARCH_TARGET_ROLE to document the paired HF, UF, or external
#   collector role.
# SPLUNK_PROFILE="cloud"
# SPLUNK_SEARCH_PROFILE="hf"
# SPLUNK_INGEST_PROFILE="hf"
# SPLUNK_DEPLOYER_PROFILE="deployer"
# SPLUNK_CLUSTER_MANAGER_PROFILE="cluster_manager"
# SPLUNK_TARGET_ROLE="search-tier"
# SPLUNK_SEARCH_TARGET_ROLE="heavy-forwarder"

# --- Cloud profile template ---
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_PLATFORM="cloud"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_TARGET_ROLE="search-tier"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_HOST="your-stack.stg.splunkcloud.com"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_MGMT_PORT="8089"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_SEARCH_API_URI="https://your-stack.stg.splunkcloud.com:8089"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_URI="${SPLUNK_SEARCH_API_URI}"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_USER="${STACK_USERNAME}"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_PASS="${STACK_PASSWORD}"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_CLOUD_STACK="your-stack"
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_CLOUD_SEARCH_HEAD=""
# PROFILE_cloud__SPLUNK_CLOUD_INDEX_SEARCHABLE_DAYS="90"
# PROFILE_cloud__ACS_SERVER="https://staging.admin.splunk.com"
# PROFILE_cloud__STACK_TOKEN=""
# PROFILE_cloud__STACK_USERNAME=""
# PROFILE_cloud__STACK_PASSWORD=""
# PROFILE_cloud__STACK_TOKEN_USER=""

# --- Optional temporary direct search-head profile for Cloud search-tier REST.
# Use this only when the load-balanced stack hostname is inconsistent during a
# rolling restart or right after a Cloud app install.
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_PLATFORM="cloud"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_TARGET_ROLE="search-tier"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_SEARCH_API_URI="https://sh-i-REPLACE_ME.your-stack.stg.splunkcloud.com:8089"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_URI="${SPLUNK_SEARCH_API_URI}"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_USER="${STACK_USERNAME}"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_PASS="${STACK_PASSWORD}"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__SPLUNK_CLOUD_STACK="your-stack"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__ACS_SERVER="https://staging.admin.splunk.com"
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__STACK_TOKEN=""
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__STACK_USERNAME=""
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__STACK_PASSWORD=""
# PROFILE_cloud_direct__STACK_TOKEN_USER=""

